      "writtenOn": "2019-11-02T06:33:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "this logging is OK during development, but otherwise it should not be here. Normally an app initializes context with logging and all logs go into one place. These logs would make little sense in the global log. It is like an HTTP library logged something about TCP and your server logs were full of those details. What generic libs do instead is return errors annotation with additional information, e.g. errors.Annotate. \n\nThe biggest offender is L134. It violates \"only handle error once\" rule, see https://dave.cheney.net/2016/04/27/dont-just-check-errors-handle-them-gracefully\nit assumes that the caller won\u0027t log the error. if it does, then we log the same message twice, potentially with different severity level",
      "revId": "6b6a0892837873ad614239efd435c28409ed0c29",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
